{{infobox ethnic group | group = Thuri / Shatt | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = | caption = | region1 = {{flag|South Sudan}} | pop1 = {{circa}} 9,000<ref name="thuri"/> | langs = [[Dhethuri language|Thuri]] | rels = [[Traditional African religions|Thuri ethnic religions]], [[Christianity]]<ref name="thuri"/> | related = [[Luo peoples]], [[Dār Fertit|Fertit peoples]] }}
The '''Thuri''', also known as '''Shatt''',{{sfnp|Blocq|2017|p=178}} are a [[Dār Fertit|Fertit tribe]]{{sfnp|Blocq|2017|p=178}} and [[Luo peoples|Luo people]] of [[South Sudan]].<ref name="thuri">{{cite news |url=https://joshuaproject.net/people_groups/11547/OD |title=Dhr Thuri, Wada in South Sudan |author=Angelo Ugwaag wod Arun |work=[[Joshua Project]] |date= |accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref> They speak [[Dhethuri language|Thuri]], a [[Luo language]]<ref name="thuri"/> that is similar to the [[Jur language|Jur]] and [[Dinka language]]s.{{sfnp|Blocq|2017|p=178}} Having been perceived as close to the [[Dinka people]], the Thuri were targets of ethnic violence during the [[Second Sudanese Civil War]], when the "[[Army of Peace]]", a mostly Fertit pro-government militia, attacked them as supporters of the mostly Dinka [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] rebels. This caused many Thuri to take up arms and to join the SPLA in order to take revenge against other Fertit groups.{{sfnp|Blocq|2017|p=178}}
