{{Globalize/US|date=November 2017}} [[Image:Religion economy.png|thumb|350px|[[GDP per capita|The average annual income]] of countries correlates negatively [[Importance of religion by country|with national levels of religiosity]].<ref name=WIN-Gallup>{{cite web|last=WIN-Gallup|title=Global Index of religion and atheism.|url=http://redcresearch.ie/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/RED-C-press-release-Religion-and-Atheism-25-7-12.pdf|accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>]] The correlation between '''wealth and religion''' has been subject to academic research. [[Wealth]] is the status of being the beneficiary or proprietor of a large accumulation of [[Capital (economics)|capital]] and [[economic power]]. [[Religion]] is a [[cultural system]] that often involves belief in [[supernatural]] forces and may intend to provide a moral system or a meaning of life.
The [[GDP]] of countries generally correlates negatively with their religiosity, i.e. the wealthier a population is the more secular it is.<ref>{{cite web|author=Survey Reports |url=http://pewglobal.org/reports/display.php?ReportID=258 |title=World Publics Welcome Global Trade — But Not Immigration &#124; Pew Global Attitudes Project |publisher=Pewglobal.org |date= |accessdate=2011-10-21}}</ref>
==Statistics==
=== Global === According to a study from 2015, [[Christians]] hold the largest amount of wealth (55% of the total world wealth), followed by [[Muslims]] (5.0%), [[Hindus]] (3.3%), and [[Jews]] (1.1%). According to the same study it was found that adherents under the classification [[Irreligion]] or other religions hold about 34.8% of the total global wealth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/453467/christians-hold-largest-percentage-global.html6 |title=Christians hold largest percentage of global wealth: Report|publisher=deccanherald.com|date=2015-01-14}}</ref>
A study done by the nonpartisan wealth research firm New World Wealth found that 56.2% of the 13.1 million millionaires in the world were Christians,<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2015/01/14/the-religion-of-millionaires-.html The religion of millionaires]</ref> while 6.5% were Muslims, 3.9% were Hindu, and 1.7% were Jewish; 31.7% were identified as adherents of "other" religions or "not religious".
=== United States === [[File:Income Ranking by Religious Group - 2000.png|thumb|550px|A chart illustrating income by religious grouping in the US in 2001]]
A study in the [[United States]] (based on data from 1985–1998), conducted by the sociologist Lisa A. Keister and published in the ''[[Social Forces]]'' journal, found that adherents of [[Judaism]] and [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalianism]]{{sfn|Allen|1975}} accumulated the most wealth, believers in [[Catholicism]] and mainline [[Protestants]] were in the middle, while conservative Protestants accumulated the least; in general, people who attend religious services accumulated more wealth than those who do not (taking into account variations of education and other factors).<ref name="ohio">{{cite web|url=http://researchnews.osu.edu/archive/relgwlth.htm |title=Religion Helps Shape Wealth Of Americans, Study Finds |publisher=Researchnews.osu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-10-21}}</ref> Keister suggested that wealth accumulation is shaped by [[family]] processes.{{sfn|Keister|2003}}
In the United States, 48% of [[Hindu]]s have a [[household income]] of $100,000 or more, and 70% make at least $75,000, which is the highest among all religions in United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/hinds_most_educated_highest_earning_religion/1449355.html|title=Hindu-Americans Rank Top in Education, Income|accessdate=Dec 1, 2012}}</ref> The median [[net worth]] of people believing in [[Judaism]] is calculated at 150,890 [[USD]], while the median net worth of conservative [[Protestants]] (including [[Baptists]], [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventists]], [[Christian Scientists]]) was 26,200 USD. The overall median in the dataset was 48,200 USD.<ref name="ohio"/>
According to a 2014 study by the [[Pew Research Center]], Jewish ranked as the most financially successful religious group in the United States, with 44% of Jewish living in households with incomes of at least $100,000, followed by [[Hindu]] (36%), [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalians]] (35%), and [[Presbyterian Church (USA)|Presbyterians]] (32%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2016/10/11/how-income-varies-among-u-s-religious-groups/|title=How income varies among U.S. religious groups|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=2016-10-16}}</ref> Amongst Jews, in 2016, [[Modern Orthodox Jews]] had a median household income of $158,000, while [[Open Orthodoxy]] Jews had a median household income of $185,000 (compared to the American median household income of $59,000 in 2016).<ref>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/5-key-takeaways-some-surprising-from-new-survey-of-us-modern-orthodox-jews 5 key takeaways, some surprising, from new survey of US Modern Orthodox Jews] By BEN SALES 30 September 2017, JTA</ref>
According to the same study there is correlation between education and income, about 77% of American Hindus have an [[Academic degree|undergraduate]] degree, followed by Jews (59%), [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalians]] (56%), and [[Presbyterian Church (USA)|Presbyterians]] (47%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2016/11/04/the-most-and-least-educated-u-s-religious-groups/|title=The most and least educated U.S. religious group|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=2016-10-16}}</ref>
==Explanations== A study published in the ''[[American Journal of Sociology]]'' by Lisa Keister, found that "religion affects wealth indirectly through educational attainment, fertility, and female labor force participation" but also found some evidence of direct effects of religion on wealth attainment.{{sfn|Keister|2008}} Keister notes that certain religious beliefs ("one should have many children", "women should not work") lower wealth accumulation, both on the micro- and macro-scale.{{sfn|Keister|2008}}<ref name="Keister2">{{cite news |last=Keister |first=Lisa A. |date=2 November 2011 |title=How Religion Contributes to Wealth and Poverty |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/lisa-a-keister/religion-contributes-wealth-poverty_b_1069766.html |work=The Huffington Post |access-date=19 November 2017}}</ref>
