The '''Yarse''', also spelt '''Yarsé''', '''Yarsin'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://base.afrique-gouvernance.net/docs/rapportfinal_lcspboromo20071erepartie_fr.pdf|title=État et contexte de la fourniture de services publics dans la commune urbaine de Boromo (Province des Balé, Burkina Faso) Première partie. Synthèse des résultats|last=Jean-Pierre Jacob, Peter Hochet|first=|date=1 May 2007|website=|page=9|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=30 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xFcQBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=burkina+%22yarsin%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1uN7L9I3TAhUqAcAKHTruAU8Q6AEIIzAB#v=onepage&q=yarsin&f=false|title=The Legacy of Arab-Islam In Africa: A Quest for Inter-religious Dialogue|last=Azumah|first=John Alembillah|date=2014-10-01|publisher=Oneworld Publications|year=|isbn=9781780746852|location=|pages=|language=en|chapter=The Socio-Religious Dynamics}}</ref> or '''Yarcin''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legiburkina.bf/m/Sommaires_JO/Arr%C3%AAt%C3%A9_MATD_2009_00076.htm|title=Arrêté n°2009-076/MATD/SG/DGCAF/DOAT du 09 octobre 2009. JO N° 51 DU 17 DECEMBRE 2009|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=30 March 2017}}</ref> are a people of [[Burkina Faso]], living among the [[Mossi people|Mossi]]. The population in the mid-1990s was estimated at 190,000, of whom 90% were Muslims.<ref>James S. Olson, ''The Peoples of Africa: An Ethnohistorical Dictionary'' (Greenwood Publishing Group, 1996; {{ISBN|0313279187}}), p. 603.</ref>
They are the descendants of [[Mandinka people|Mandinka]] traders who arrived in the area in the late 1600s, bringing [[Islam]]. In 1780, they were granted permission by the Mossi king to settle throughout his kingdom; over the years, they adopted the language and customs of the Mossi and intermarried with them, but they did not convert either to Christianity or the indigenous Mossi religion, remaining faithful to Islam. Settlements in which the Yarse stayed included [[Kaya, Burkina Faso|Kaya]], [[Rakaye Yarcé|Rakaye]], Patenga and, later in the 18th century, [[Ouagadougou]], where they had their own quarter.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=frC8SAu9QxQC&pg=PA342&dq=burkina+%22yarse%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwialb2e9I3TAhXGI8AKHT58Ds84ChDoAQhRMAk#v=onepage&q=burkina%20%22yarse%22&f=false|title=The Archaeology of Islam in Sub-Saharan Africa|last=Insoll|first=Timothy|date=2003-07-03|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521657020|language=en}}</ref> They continue to be merchants, although many have settled down to become subsistence [[millet]] farmers.<ref>Olson, ''The Peoples of Africa: An Ethnohistorical Dictionary'', p. 603.</ref>
